Typically you would use a hashed counter; simply maintain a counter from 0 to 11,881,375 and apply some bijective mapping function to that so they&#39;re produced in random order.

Something like:

    // map any value &lt; 2**24 to another value &lt; 2**24, with no duplicates
    int hash24(int x) {
      x = x ^ (x &gt;&gt; 12);
      x = (x * 0x818d6b) &amp; 0xffffff;
      x = x ^ (x &gt;&gt; 10);
      x = (x * 0x0fa653) &amp; 0xffffff;
      x = x ^ (x &gt;&gt; 12);
      return x;
    }

    void next(char result[6]) {
      static int s = 0;    // keep this value somewhere persistent
      const int seq = 0x55aa55;    // change this to re-randomize
      int r;

      // find the next random value less than 26**5
      do {
        r = hash24(s ^ seq);
        s = s + 1;
      } while (result &gt;= 11881376);

      // map integer to string of letters
      for (int i = 0; i &lt; 5; ++i) {
        result[i] = &#39;a&#39; + (r % 26);
        r /= 26;
      }
      result[5] = &#39;\0&#39;;
    }


However, it seems likely that you have more constraints which you haven&#39;t mentioned.  You might want to avoid words that won&#39;t be memorable because they&#39;re perfect gibberish (like a YouTube URL) and at the same time you might want to avoid offensive words (no idea if YouTube filters these, but I haven&#39;t seen one).


Because 26 is divisible by two it&#39;s fairly straightforward to make a version that doesn&#39;t rely on rejecting out-of-range values, but it&#39;s an unnecessarily weird thing to do:

    int hash26p5(int x) {
      int r[5] = { 5, 11, 17, 23, 27 };
      for (int i = 0; i &lt; 5; ++i) {
        int r = ((x &amp; 31) * r[i]) &amp; 31;
        x = (x &gt;&gt; 5) + r * 371293;
      }
      return x;
    }

    void next(char result[6]) {
      static int s = 0;    // keep this value somewhere persistent
      int r hash26p5(s);
      s = s + 1;

      // map integer to string of letters
      for (int i = 0; i &lt; 5; ++i) {
        result[i] = &#39;a&#39; + (r % 26);
        r /= 26;
      }
      result[5] = &#39;\0&#39;;
    }

In fact, because there are only two prime factors more interesting things can be done, but they&#39;re even more esoteric, and they wouldn&#39;t be relevant if you moved to a smaller alphabet or a different number of letters.

